                               @"Created fifty states",
                               @"Brought Christopher Columbus to the US"],
               ExplanationKey: @"The Declaration of Independence contains important ideas about the American system of government. The Declaration of Independence states that all people are created equal and have “certain unalienable rights.” These are rights that no government can change or take away. The author of the Declaration, Thomas Jefferson, wrote that the American colonies should be independent because Great Britain did not respect the basic rights of people in the colonies. Jefferson believed that a government exists only if the people think it should. He believed in the idea that the people create their own government and consent, or agree, to follow laws their government makes."
               },
             @{QuestionNumberKey: @"9",
               QuestionTitleKey: @"What are two rights in the Declaration of Independence?",
               AnswersNeededKey: @2,
